Robert Decherd

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia


					Jump to:					navigation, 					search






This biography of a living person needs additional citations for verification. Please help by adding reliable sources. Contentious material about living persons that is unsourced or poorly sourced must be removed immediately, especially if potentially libelous or harmful. (April 2011) (Learn how and when to remove this template message)


Robert Decherd (born 1951) is an American businessman. From 1987 to 2013,[1] he served as the Chairman of the Board, President, and Chief Executive Officer of A. H. Belo Corporation of Dallas, which owns newspapers in North Texas, most notably The Dallas Morning News.[2]



Contents


1 Career
2 See also
3 References
4 Further reading



Career[edit]
Decherd graduated from St. Mark's School of Texas, where he was editor of the school newspaper. He then attended Harvard, where he became President of The Harvard Crimson and Orator of his class
Decherd became Belo's chairman and chief executive officer in January 1987. He became President of Belo in January 1994; he had previously served as President from January 1985 through December 1986. From January 1984 through December 1986, he served as Chief Operating Officer. In these roles, he oversaw Belo's listing as a public company with the New York Stock Exchange in 1983, as well as the biggest transaction in the company's history, Belo's acquisition of The Providence Journal Company in 1997.
Decherd retired from Belo in 2013, after having started in the newspaper business upon his graduation from college forty years earlier.[3]
Decherd's great-grandfather was George Dealey, the founder of the Dallas Morning News and namesake of Dealey Plaza.[4] His father, H. Ben Decherd, had also been the CEO of Belo.[5]
Decherd is a member of the board of directors, lead director, and chairman of the Executive Committee of Kimberly-Clark Corporation. He also serves on the Advisory Council for Harvard University's Center for Ethics and the Professions. He was a member of the Media Security and Reliability Council, which was part of President Bush's Homeland Security initiative.
He received the Media Institute's 1999 Freedom of Speech Award.
